## Thesis Word Assembly Lessons

- Do not write multiple logical paragraphs into one Word paragraph via a single `Range.Text` containing embedded carriage returns. This causes heading/body merges and broken styles from later versions.
- Do not anchor appendix insertion by searching plain text like `附录...` without distinguishing TOC entries from body content; this can accidentally inject appendix content into the directory section.
- For chapter repair in Word, prefer:
  - replace heading paragraph only
  - insert new body paragraphs separately
  - insert next chapter heading as its own paragraph
  - append appendix content only at the true document end
- When regenerating a thesis DOCX, unify TOC styles (`目录 1`, `目录 2`, `目录 3`) alongside body styles. Do not assume the table of contents will stay correct after heading/style edits.
- If heading fonts are normalized, update the TOC and then explicitly normalize TOC fonts, size, color, indentation, and line spacing to match the template baseline.
- Treat standalone institutional/front-matter headings such as `大连科技学院`, `毕业设计（论文）原创承诺书`, `参考文献`, `致谢`, and `附录：程序代码（含详细注释）` as title-level headings, not body text.
- Never classify front-matter title pages or appendix opening pages by content generation heuristics alone; explicitly preserve their heading role and typography.
- When fixing thesis formatting, do not rely on a single global rule for all non-numbered paragraphs. Some non-numbered paragraphs are major headings and must inherit heading formatting.
- Before finalizing a thesis DOCX, run a heading audit for chapter titles, second-level titles, third-level titles, appendix title, reference title, acknowledgement title, and front-matter title pages.
- If a paragraph contains multiple logical blocks merged into one paragraph, do not continue styling downstream content until the merged paragraph is split back into separate paragraphs.
